Description: A jar-stopper: in relief, within a raised edge, is a cobra to right, with disc above head; behind is the Latin letter L, in front the letter H (Year 7); rough, rounded back. Pressed over a modelled form. Micaceous brown Nile silt, with a paler core, burnt black in places.
Curator's comments: Terracotta IV Donated: Henri Chiha, a resident of Cairo. Roman, about mid-first to mid-second century AD. Comparanda: Plaster and fired-clay stoppers with a cobra, usually crowned, and often with letters or names: Johnson 1979: 235, pl. 75:d-f, from Myos Hormos, dated first century AD; Sundelin 1996: 300-2, fig. 16-1, pl. 16-2, from Berenike, dated late first century AD; Cashman et al. 1999: 287, fig. 15:2, from Berenike, context of late first century BC to first century AD; Thomas 2001: 54, fig. 13.2, from Myos Hormos, dated late first to second century AD; Thomas 2002: 66, fig. 44, no. ST 0259, from Myos Hormos, probably first or second century AD; Thomas 2003: 69, fig. 57, five examples, from Myos Hormos, from contexts of mid-first to mid-second century AD. A wooden stamp for a stopper with a cobra (reversed to ours) and a suggested Aramaic inscription comes from Narmuthis: Bresciani 1968: 30, fig. 3, pls A:1 and X:1-3, dated fourth to third century BC.
Bibliographic references: Terracotta / Catalogue of Terracottas in the British Museum (3610)
